===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|en|enm|braiden}}, {{m|enm|breiden}}, {{m|enm|bræiden}}, from {{inh|en|ang|breġdan||to move quickly, pull, shake, swing, throw (wrestling), draw (sword), drag; bend, weave, braid, knit, join together; change color, vary, be transformed; bind, knot; move, be pulled; flash}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*bregdan}}, from {{der|en|gem-pro|*bregdaną||to flicker, flutter, jerk, tug, twitch, flinch, move, swing}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*bʰrēḱ-}}, {{m|ine-pro|*bʰrēǵ-||to shine, shimmer}}. 

Cognate with Scots {{cog|sco|brade}}, {{cog|sco|braid||to move quickly or suddenly}}, {{cog|stq|braidje||to knit}}, {{cog|fy|breidzje}}, Dutch {{m|nl|breien||to knit}}, {{cog|nds|breiden}}, {{cog|de|breiden}}, {{cog|bar|bretten||to move quickly, twitch}}, {{cog|is|bregða||to move quickly, jerk}}, {{cog|fo|bregða||to move quickly, react swiftly; to draw (sword)}} and {{cog|fo|bregda||to plaid, braid, twist, twine}}.

